Random effects regression model

We’ll first consider the baseline fixed effects considering only the continuous variables. We have:

\[\widehat{marks} = b_{int} + b_{SecResp} * SecResp + b_{SecPg} * SecPg + \\ b_{RespInter} * RespInter + b_{InputInter} * InputInter + b_{CntResp} * CntResp + \epsilon \] Where, \(\epsilon \sim \mathcal{N}(0,~\sigma)\)

Building on this, we add in all of our fixed factor terms: method factor, data dimension, variance-covariance shape, signal mixing location. Lastly we add the random effect of the participants. This random term, \(effect_{participant}\), accounts for the difference between participant, that is the each individuals ability/disposition to effect their task marks. Then our mixed model is:

\[\widehat{marks} = b_{int} + b_{SecResp} * SecResp + b_{SecPg} * SecPg + \\ b_{RespInter} * RespInter + b_{InputInter} * InputInter + b_{CntResp} * \\ b_{factor} * I(factor) + b_{dim} * I(dim) + b_{shape} * I(shape) + \\ b_{location} * I(location) + b_{participant} * effect_{participant} + \epsilon\] Where,
\[\epsilon \sim \mathcal{N}(0,~\sigma) \\ effect_{participant} \sim \mathcal{N}(0,~\sigma_{participant}) \\ factor \in (pca, grand*, radial) \\ dim \in (4, 6) \text{ variables, with 3 and 4 clusters respectivly} \\ shape \in (EEE, EEV, EVV~banana) \\ location \in (0/100, 33/66, 50/50) \text{ % mixing of a noise and signal variable respectively} \\ I() \text{ is the indicator function, a logical value for each level of the fixed factor}\]
